  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Left Ventricular Assist Device (LVAD) implantation is a common surgical procedure in patients
      with end-stage heart failure. Optimal fluid management is essential for adequate
      postoperative treatment. It is important to identify which patients will benefit from fluid
      administration. Passive leg raising (PLR) is a validated dynamic method to predict fluid
      responsiveness in patients with heart failure by inducing a transient increase in cardiac
      preload. Objective: To investigate the role of PLR on the management of patients following
      LVAD implantation in the postoperative period.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
